\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs32\b1 4}{\f0\fs24  (20:11\endash 13) }{\f0\fs24\b1 Confession}{\f0\fs24 : God secured the believer through an honest confession of sin. Remember, Abraham did not know that God had appeared to the king in a dream. In Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s mind, he had only one hope, only one chance to save himself before the king: tell the truth. He had to confess his sin and shame, trusting that God would move upon the king\u8217\'92s heart to spare him from execution. Abraham was, of course, confessing before God while he was confessing to the king. In fact, confessing to a person that one has sinned against him is the most difficult confession to make. Note Abraham\u8217\'92s confession.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 a. He confessed the sin of fear, of not trusting God to take care of him and Sarah (v. 1). Abraham confessed that he feared the Philistines, that they would kill him for his wife. Note why he feared them: because he did not sense a fear of God among the Philistines. They were living just as all the other people in Canaan were: living selfish, immoral and lawless lives. Consequently, Abraham feared that their selfish, immoral, and lawless spirit would take action against him. He just failed to trust God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s care; his fear was greater than his trust of God, at least in these circumstances.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 b. He confessed the sin of lying, of twisting the truth, of telling half-truths (v. 12). Sarah was his half-sister, the daughter of his father, not of his mother.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 c. Abraham confessed the sin of misusing and exploiting people (v. 13). Abraham confessed that he had made this claim throughout his life, that he had led Sarah to go along with the scheme from the beginning of their journey to the promised land (v. 13). This was a horrible sin: that of misusing and exploiting Sarah, of dishonoring and shaming her, and of risking her life if the king or noblemen were displeased with her. It is possible that the king Abimelech had taken Sarah into his harem in order to make an alliance with Abraham. Remember, Abraham was a powerful sheik at that time. Nevertheless, Abraham had lied and misused Sarah to protect his own life, and he stood guilty of the charges: he had shamed and dishonored his wife, misused her to protect himself. This must have been an extremely difficult confession to make. But Abraham had to confess the sin, for he was guilty before God and the king.}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24 . God keeps and secures us through confession of sins. We are saved and we are kept by confession.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge20.11-13&off=0&ctx=eby%E2%80%9D+(He.+12:9%E2%80%9311).%0a~4+(20:11%E2%80%9313)+Confess"}{\fldrslt\f3\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 113). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24 . God often keeps and secures the believer through a human rebuke and chastisement, through the rebuke and chastisement of other people. In love, God sees to it that we are rebuked and chastised so that we will be embarrassed and shamed and stop our sin and live like we should.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 (1)\tab God sees to it that we are often rebuked and corrected by other people.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge20.8-10&off=3356&ctx=rebuke+of+the+king.%0a~Thought+1.+God+often"}{\fldrslt\f3\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 112). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
